content.title: 行方不明のドバイ王女は「家に帰っても安全」 -  Independent.ie
content.desc: The government of Dubai broke its silence on the case of its missing princess yesterday, saying she was safely back home and accusing a former French spy of her kidnap. Sheikha Latifa, the daughter of Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid al-Maktoum, Dubai's ruler, tried to escape the country in March after saying she was effectively being held prisoner by her repressive father. She fled across the border to Oman with the help of a friend, before boarding a boat to meet French national Herve Jaubert, who had himself escaped the Emirates in 2008. content.title: 行方不明のエミラティ王女の家族は、彼女が家で「安全」であると言います - ガーディアン
content.desc: A missing Emirati princess, who witnesses said was seized by commandos from a yacht after trying to flee Dubai, is “safe” at home, according to a statement released by her family. The statement did not include any video or other message from Sheikha Latifa bint Mohammed al-Maktoum herself, who was 33 on Wednesday. In a video Latifa made before her failed escape from the kingdom, she said she feared torture or worse if captured. content.desc: An Emirati princess who has been missing since being forcibly detained while fleeing her home country nine months ago is back in Dubai, according to a statement from the government. Sheikha Latifa bint Mohammed al-Maktoum, the daughter of the prime minister of the United Arab Emirates, has not been heard from since she was seized from a boat off the coast of India in March by what witnesses said were armed men.
